{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_81","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"source .venv/bin/activate && python - <<'PY'\nimport pandas as pd\nse = pd.read_json('results/semeval_subtaskB_predictions.jsonl', lines=True)\nprint(se[['true_model','pred_model']].value_counts().head(30))\nfor label in ['human','chatGPT','cohere','davinci','bloomz','dolly']:\n    row = se[se['true_model']==label].iloc[0]\n    print('\\\\nTRUE', label, 'PRED', row['pred_model'])\n    print(row['text'][:700].replace('\\\\n',' '))\n    print(row['probabilities'])\nPY\"","aggregated_output":"true_model  pred_model\nhuman       human         29\ndavinci     chatGPT       28\ncohere      chatGPT       25\nbloomz      chatGPT       18\ndolly       chatGPT       18\nchatGPT     chatGPT       17\n            human         13\nbloomz      human         12\ndolly       human         11\ncohere      human          5\ndavinci     human          2\nhuman       chatGPT        1\ndolly       davinci        1\nName: count, dtype: int64\n\nTRUE human PRED human\nThank you for the review! We will take the comments into account and endeavour to make the text even clearer.  A quick comment about motivation: our goal in this work improve interpretability in deep neural networks through a better understanding of neural network expressivity. In particular, we look at different \"diagnostics\" (transitions/activation patterns/dichotomies) for measuring the expressiveness of different neural network architectures, and their practical consequences. The surprising fact that three natural measures of expressiveness are related by *direct* proportion (see below) to trajectory length suggests consequences on remaining depth (earlier parameters are more important t\n{'human': 0.85, 'chatGPT': 0.05, 'cohere': 0.02, 'davinci': 0.03, 'bloomz': 0.02, 'dolly': 0.03}\n\nTRUE chatGPT PRED chatGPT\nThe paper proposes a new approach to training sequence models by using reinforcement learning (RL) in conjunction with a pre-trained Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) as a way to address known failure modes associated with supervised learning and next-step prediction. Specifically, in the proposed approach, a part of the reward value is supplied by the pre-trained RNN which is then used to optimize for imposed reward functions in the RL model. The proposed approach is demonstrated in the context of music generation, where an LSTM is trained on a large corpus of songs to predict the next note in a musical sequence. The authors show that by combining maximum likelihood (ML) and RL in this way, th\n{'human': 0.1, 'chatGPT': 0.7000000000000001, 'cohere': 0.05, 'davinci': 0.1, 'bloomz': 0.03, 'dolly': 0.02}\n\nTRUE cohere PRED chatGPT\n The paper \"Do Deep Convolutional Nets Really Need to be Deep and Convolutional?\" provides evidence that deep convolutional networks really need to be both deep and convolutional in order to be accurate. The authors use a technique called distillation to train smaller, shallower networks to mimic the behavior of larger, deeper networks. They find that while this technique can produce networks that are as accurate as the larger networks, these shallower networks still need to contain multiple layers of convolution in order to be effective. This provides evidence that depth and convolutionality are both important factors in the effectiveness of convolutional networks.\n{'human': 0.1, 'chatGPT': 0.6000000000000001, 'cohere': 0.1, 'davinci': 0.1, 'bloomz': 0.05, 'dolly': 0.05}\n\nTRUE davinci PRED chatGPT\n  This paper addresses the problem of applying adversarial machine learning at scale. Adversarial machine learning is a type of machine learning that involves an attacker attempting to manipulate a model's output by providing malicious input. The paper explores the challenges of scaling adversarial machine learning and proposes a number of strategies to address them.  Strengths:  The paper presents a comprehensive overview of the challenges of scaling adversarial machine learning, as well as a number of strategies to address them. The authors provide a thorough discussion of the various approaches to scaling adversarial machine learning, and their relative merits. The paper also provides an \n{'human': 0.1, 'chatGPT': 0.6000000000000001, 'cohere': 0.1, 'davinci': 0.1, 'bloomz': 0.05, 'dolly': 0.05}\n\nTRUE bloomz PRED chatGPT\nThe authors present an interesting approach to sequence decomposition that is based on latent variable models.  The main idea of their method is to use probabilistic graphical models (PGM) for representing sequences as well as decomposing them into sub-sequences. In particular they propose two different types of PGMs - Hidden Markov Models  (HMMs)  and Conditional Random Fields  - which are used in combination with Expectation Maximization algorithms for learning parameters from data sets consisting of multiple time series.  Their experiments show promising results when applied to real world problems such as speech recognition,  gesture recognition ,and human activity analysis . Strengths:  \n{'human': 0.1, 'chatGPT': 0.6000000000000001, 'cohere': 0.1, 'davinci': 0.1, 'bloomz': 0.05, 'dolly': 0.05}\n\nTRUE dolly PRED chatGPT\nThis paper presents a model for running deep neural networks on very large datasets made up of records of many features. The model is called Paleocaching and is based on the idea of cross-validation prediction latency hiding by asynchronous updating and aggregation of result curently used in GPU compute clusters. The key insight is that the training process resembles a cache fill, where the target labels for each observation are analogous to an inputbuffer in a CPU cache. When a batch of data is fetched from the training set by the model, this input buffer is filled with the new values. The filling of the buffer is asynchronous, so the latency of the network training is hidden by dividing up\n{'human': 0.1, 'chatGPT': 0.6000000000000001, 'cohere': 0.1, 'davinci': 0.1, 'bloomz': 0.05, 'dolly': 0.05}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_83","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"source .venv/bin/activate && python - <<'PY'\nimport pandas as pd\ncustom = pd.read_json('results/custom_mode_predictions.jsonl', lines=True)\nprint(custom[['mode','pred_mode']].value_counts().head(20))\nfor mode in ['human_original','human_polished','llm_generated','llm_humanized','dictated_spoken','keyboard_noisy']:\n    row = custom[custom['mode']==mode].iloc[0]\n    print('\\\\nMODE', mode)\n    print(row['text'][:900].replace('\\\\n',' '))\n    print('PRED', row['pred_mode'])\n    print('PROBS', row['probabilities'])\nPY\"","aggregated_output":"mode             pred_mode      \nhuman_original   human_original     60\nllm_generated    llm_generated      60\nllm_humanized    llm_humanized      60\nhuman_polished   human_polished     60\ndictated_spoken  dictated_spoken    60\nkeyboard_noisy   keyboard_noisy     60\nName: count, dtype: int64\n\nMODE human_original\nA dwarf planet is a planetary-mass object that is neither a planet nor a satellite .More explicitly, the International Astronomical Union (IAU) defines a dwarf planet as a celestial body in direct orbit of the Sun that is massive enough for its shape to be controlled by gravitation , but that unlike a planet has not cleared its orbital region of other objects.\nPRED human_original\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.85, 'llm_generated': 0.05, 'llm_humanized': 0.02, 'human_polished': 0.05, 'dictated_spoken': 0.01, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.02}\n\nMODE human_polished\nAtherosclerosis, also known as arteriosclerotic vascular disease (ASVD), is a condition where the walls of arteries thicken due to the accumulation of fatty materials such as cholesterol and triglycerides. This syndrome affects arterial blood vessels and is characterized by a chronic inflammatory response in the artery walls, mainly caused by the buildup of macrophage white blood cells. This process is promoted by low-density lipoproteins (LDL), which carry cholesterol and triglycerides, especially when there is insufficient removal of fats and cholesterol by high-density lipoproteins (HDL). Commonly referred to as 'hardening' or 'furring' of the arteries, atherosclerosis is caused by the formation of multiple plaques within the arteries.\nPRED human_polished\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.05, 'llm_generated': 0.1, 'llm_humanized': 0.05, 'human_polished': 0.75, 'dictated_spoken': 0.03, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.02}\n\nMODE llm_generated\nAtherosclerotic heart disease is a condition in which the arteries that supply blood to the heart become narrowed and hardened due to the buildup of fatty deposits, such as cholesterol and triglycerides, on their inner walls. This process, known as atherosclerosis, leads to chronic inflammation and the formation of plaques, which can restrict blood flow and increase the risk of heart attacks and other cardiovascular complications.\nPRED llm_generated\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.05, 'llm_generated': 0.85, 'llm_humanized': 0.05, 'human_polished': 0.03, 'dictated_spoken': 0.01, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.01}\n\nMODE llm_humanized\nSo, atherosclerotic heart disease basically happens when the arteries that feed your heart get clogged up with fatty stuff like cholesterol. Over time, these buildups, or plaques, make the artery walls thicker and less flexible, which can slow down or block blood flow. That’s what people mean when they talk about 'hardening of the arteries,' and it’s a big reason for heart problems like heart attacks.\nPRED llm_humanized\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.03, 'llm_generated': 0.1, 'llm_humanized': 0.8, 'human_polished': 0.04, 'dictated_spoken': 0.02, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.01}\n\nMODE dictated_spoken\nOkay so atherosclerosis, sometimes called arteriosclerotic vascular disease or ASVD, is when the walls of your arteries get thicker because fatty stuff like cholesterol and triglycerides builds up there. It’s a syndrome that affects your blood vessels, and it’s basically a long-term inflammation in the artery walls. That happens mostly because white blood cells called macrophages pile up, and it gets worse if there’s too much LDL, that’s the bad cholesterol, and not enough HDL, which is the good cholesterol that helps clear out fats. People often call it hardening or furring of the arteries, and it’s really about these plaques forming inside the arteries.\nPRED dictated_spoken\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.02, 'llm_generated': 0.05, 'llm_humanized': 0.1, 'human_polished': 0.03, 'dictated_spoken': 0.78, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.02}\n\nMODE keyboard_noisy\nA dwarf planet is a planetary-mass object that is neither a planet nor a satellite.More explicitly, the International Astronomical Union (JAU) defines a dwarf planet as a celestial body in dorect orbit of the Sun that is massive enough for its shape to be controlled by gravitation, but that unlike a plnaet has not cleared its obrital region of other objects.\nPRED keyboard_noisy\nPROBS {'human_original': 0.01, 'llm_generated': 0.01, 'llm_humanized': 0.01, 'human_polished': 0.02, 'dictated_spoken': 0.01, 'keyboard_noisy': 0.9400000000000001}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
